{
  "subject_id": "mba102",
  "title": "Managerial Economics",
  "modules": [
    {
      "module_id": "m1",
      "title": "Demand and Supply Analysis",
      "topics": [
        {
          "topic_id": "t1",
          "title": "Law of Demand",
          "difficulty": "easy",
          "estimated_time": "15 min",
          "prerequisites": [],
          "learning_outcomes": [
            "Understand demand behavior",
            "Interpret demand curve"
          ],
          "content": "## Law of Demand\nThe law of demand states that, holding other factors constant, quantity demanded decreases when price increases.\n\n### Demand Curve\nDownward sloping due to income and substitution effects.\n\n### Determinants\n- Income\n- Preferences\n- Prices of substitutes/complements\n\n### Exceptions\n- Giffen goods\n- Veblen goods\n\n### Managerial Relevance\nHelps firms forecast demand and set pricing strategies.",
          "examples": [
            "Discount increases sales volume",
            "Luxury pricing increases demand perception"
          ],
          "common_mistakes": [
            "Assuming demand depends only on price",
            "Ignoring external factors"
          ],
          "qna": [
            {
              "q": "What is law of demand?",
              "a": "Inverse relation between price and demand."
            },
            {
              "q": "Why downward slope?",
              "a": "Income and substitution effects."
            },
            { "q": "Exception?", "a": "Giffen goods." },
            {
              "q": "Determinants?",
              "a": "Income, preferences, related goods."
            },
            { "q": "Managerial use?", "a": "Pricing decisions." }
          ]
        },
        {
          "topic_id": "t2",
          "title": "Elasticity of Demand",
          "difficulty": "medium",
          "estimated_time": "20 min",
          "prerequisites": ["t1"],
          "learning_outcomes": [
            "Measure demand responsiveness",
            "Apply elasticity in pricing"
          ],
          "content": "## Elasticity of Demand\nElasticity measures how quantity demanded responds to price changes.\n\n### Types\n- Price elasticity\n- Income elasticity\n- Cross elasticity\n\n### Interpretation\n- Elastic (>1)\n- Inelastic (<1)\n\n### Managerial Use\nHelps maximize revenue and optimize pricing.",
          "examples": [
            "Luxury goods are elastic",
            "Essential goods are inelastic"
          ],
          "common_mistakes": [
            "Confusing slope with elasticity",
            "Ignoring time factor"
          ],
          "qna": [
            { "q": "What is elasticity?", "a": "Responsiveness of demand." },
            { "q": "Elastic demand?", "a": "Greater than 1." },
            { "q": "Inelastic?", "a": "Less than 1." },
            { "q": "Why important?", "a": "Pricing decisions." },
            { "q": "Example?", "a": "Fuel demand is inelastic." }
          ]
        },
        {
          "topic_id": "t3",
          "title": "Supply Analysis",
          "difficulty": "easy",
          "estimated_time": "15 min",
          "prerequisites": [],
          "learning_outcomes": [
            "Understand supply behavior",
            "Analyze supply curve"
          ],
          "content": "## Supply Analysis\nSupply refers to quantity producers are willing to sell.\n\n### Law of Supply\nPrice ↑ → Supply ↑\n\n### Determinants\n- Costs\n- Technology\n- Government policies\n\n### Managerial Relevance\nHelps production planning.",
          "examples": [
            "Higher prices increase production",
            "Better tech reduces cost"
          ],
          "common_mistakes": [
            "Ignoring cost factors",
            "Assuming supply is constant"
          ],
          "qna": [
            { "q": "What is supply?", "a": "Quantity offered." },
            { "q": "Law?", "a": "Direct relationship with price." },
            { "q": "Factors?", "a": "Cost, tech." },
            { "q": "Example?", "a": "Farmers produce more at higher price." },
            { "q": "Why important?", "a": "Production planning." }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "module_id": "m2",
      "title": "Consumer Behavior",
      "topics": [
        {
          "topic_id": "t1",
          "title": "Utility Theory",
          "difficulty": "medium",
          "estimated_time": "20 min",
          "prerequisites": [],
          "learning_outcomes": [
            "Understand utility concepts",
            "Apply diminishing utility"
          ],
          "content": "## Utility Theory\nUtility measures satisfaction from consumption.\n\n### Types\n- Total utility\n- Marginal utility\n\n### Law\nMarginal utility decreases with each unit.\n\n### Managerial Relevance\nHelps product pricing and bundling.",
          "examples": ["First coffee is most satisfying", "Bulk discounts"],
          "common_mistakes": [
            "Ignoring diminishing returns",
            "Assuming constant satisfaction"
          ],
          "qna": [
            { "q": "What is utility?", "a": "Satisfaction." },
            { "q": "Marginal utility?", "a": "Extra satisfaction." },
            { "q": "Law?", "a": "Diminishing utility." },
            { "q": "Example?", "a": "Pizza slices." },
            { "q": "Use?", "a": "Pricing." }
          ]
        },
        {
          "topic_id": "t2",
          "title": "Indifference Curve Analysis",
          "difficulty": "medium",
          "estimated_time": "20 min",
          "prerequisites": ["t1"],
          "learning_outcomes": ["Understand IC properties", "Find equilibrium"],
          "content": "## Indifference Curve\nShows combinations of goods giving equal satisfaction.\n\n### Properties\n- Downward sloping\n- Convex\n\n### Consumer Equilibrium\nWhere IC touches budget line.\n\n### Managerial Use\nHelps understand preferences.",
          "examples": ["Food vs clothing choices", "Budget constraints"],
          "common_mistakes": [
            "Ignoring budget constraint",
            "Misinterpreting curves"
          ],
          "qna": [
            { "q": "What is IC?", "a": "Equal satisfaction curve." },
            { "q": "Shape?", "a": "Convex." },
            { "q": "Equilibrium?", "a": "Tangent point." },
            { "q": "Why important?", "a": "Preference analysis." },
            { "q": "Example?", "a": "Choice between goods." }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
